<promed@promedmail.org>
[Something is slightly off in this article. Rabies is a neurological
disease. The health department confirmed the cat had rabies. In order for
the health department to confirm the animal had the disease, it had to
examine the brain. In order to examine the brain the cat had to be dead.
The article states: "Untreated, rabies causes a painful death. In addition,
the cat must be euthanized or quarantined for 6 months. If it had been
vaccinated, the quarantine would have been only 45 days." If the cat had
rabies, it was euthanized in order for its brain to be tested. If a cat is
exposed but unvaccinated, it then may be quarantined for 6 months, whereas
a vaccinated cat would only be quarantined for 45 days. Exposed animals may
also be euthanized. The statement in the article was a little confusing by
not explaining that more fully. It should also be pointed out that there is
no treatment for rabies in cats as of this writing.
Cats should be vaccinated, regardless of their indoor/outdoor status. Many
states have enacted rules or legislation that requires that cats be
vaccinated with a 3-year vaccine once every 3 years. The rationale for this
requirement was that some cats suffer vaccine-related sarcomas which may
prove fatal to the cat. Although vaccine-related sarcomas are not pleasant,
it is better than exposing one's family to rabies. Vaccinating cats with a
3-year vaccine once every 3 years has reduced the rate of vaccine-related
sarcomas.
Rabies is a deadly disease, but it can present in several forms, one of
which is a change in behavior. Animals may become either aggressive or
withdrawn. Some may appear lethargic and ill, but are not recognized as
having a behavior change. Also, other diseases present in the animal, such
as liver disease, may confuse the diagnosis.
Since the couple was most likely exposed, I would hope the county health
department would be contacting them with regard to Post Exposure
Prophalaxis. - Mod.TG]
......................tg/msp/mpp

